496
00:30:00,140 --> 00:30:02,680
He has this idea called
the wooden horse, okay?

497
00:30:02,860 --> 00:30:05,060
So the Greeks pretend they give up.

498
00:30:05,140 --> 00:30:07,080
They're going to go home
because they're homesick.

499
00:30:07,220 --> 00:30:11,340
And as a present to the Trojans,

500
00:30:11,380 --> 00:30:15,720
they leave behind a wooden horse. The
Trojans take the wooden horse into the city.

501
00:30:15,840 --> 00:30:18,420
At night, the Greeks jump
out of the wooden horse,

502
00:30:18,660 --> 00:30:21,300
open the gates, and the
Trojans are slaughtered, okay?

503
00:30:21,760 --> 00:30:27,460
And this is the story of the Trojan War.

504
00:30:27,620 --> 00:30:29,180
And the Greeks love this story,

505
00:30:30,140 --> 00:30:33,660
because it's really the
Greeks being heroes, right?

506
00:30:33,940 --> 00:30:35,860
The Greeks have this great victory.

507
00:30:35,980 --> 00:30:40,560
People love to win battles. What's
amazing about Homer's story,

508
00:30:40,700 --> 00:30:44,060
okay? It's called the Iliad, and
we'll read this next semester.

509
00:30:45,200 --> 00:30:47,640
But there are three things that

510
00:30:47,640 --> 00:30:50,380
Homer does in the Iliad

511
00:30:51,020 --> 00:30:53,400
that's really never
been done before, okay?

512
00:30:54,220 --> 00:30:57,240
And so, with the Iliad, we have
the invention of literature.

513
00:30:57,660 --> 00:30:58,980
The first thing,

514
00:31:00,140 --> 00:31:03,100
that Homer does is,

515
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:08,600
rather than telling the
story from the Greek side,

516
00:31:08,880 --> 00:31:12,440
he tells the story from both
the Greek and Trojan side.

517
00:31:12,840 --> 00:31:15,720
In fact, when you read the
Iliad, you'll discover that

518
00:31:15,720 --> 00:31:18,460
the Trojans are actually more heroic,

519
00:31:18,940 --> 00:31:22,700
more courageous, and more
brave than the Greeks.

520
00:31:23,820 --> 00:31:25,460
Okay? That's pretty amazing.

521
00:31:25,780 --> 00:31:27,620
And by switching perspectives,

522
00:31:27,620 --> 00:31:31,320
a new idea comes into being

523
00:31:31,320 --> 00:31:32,840
that never really existed before.

524
00:31:32,960 --> 00:31:38,480
And we call this idea empathy. Okay?

525
00:31:38,540 --> 00:31:44,540
Empathy. The ability to see the world
from the perspective of other people.

526
00:31:45,020 --> 00:31:46,840
And before, in human civilization,

527
00:31:47,240 --> 00:31:49,040
this didn't really exist before, okay?

528
00:31:49,400 --> 00:31:52,600
But Homer creates this for the Iliad.

529
00:31:53,520 --> 00:31:55,720
The second thing that

530
00:31:55,720 --> 00:31:57,800
is new and

531
00:31:57,800 --> 00:32:00,640
unique to the Iliad is human psychology.

532
00:32:04,480 --> 00:32:06,240
So, for the first time,

533
00:32:06,280 --> 00:32:09,600
Homer discusses what motivates

534
00:32:11,320 --> 00:32:16,800
the characters in the Iliad,

535
00:32:16,860 --> 00:32:18,340
okay? Why are you fighting this war?

536
00:32:18,800 --> 00:32:23,900
And so, the story is
between two individuals,

537
00:32:24,200 --> 00:32:27,620
Achilles and King Priam.

538
00:32:28,060 --> 00:32:30,620
Okay? So, Achilles is the greatest warrior

539
00:32:31,380 --> 00:32:32,640
of the Greeks.

540
00:32:33,080 --> 00:32:35,440
Priam is the king of the Trojans.

541
00:32:35,560 --> 00:32:36,940
And they hate each other, okay?

542
00:32:36,960 --> 00:32:39,140
Because they're enemies.
Achilles is trying to kill Priam.

543
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:42,760
Priam is trying to defend
his family and his home.

544
00:32:44,160 --> 00:32:46,160
So, the Iliad starts like this.

545
00:32:46,560 --> 00:32:49,940
Achilles, at the beginning,

546
00:32:50,160 --> 00:32:53,760
gets in a fight with Agamemnon, who
is the king of the Greeks, okay?

547
00:32:53,760 --> 00:32:56,120
They get in a fight. And
they curse each other.

548
00:32:56,340 --> 00:32:58,840
And Achilles says,
You're a dog, Agamemnon.

549
00:32:59,060 --> 00:33:00,660
I'm never going to fight for you again.

550
00:33:01,040 --> 00:33:03,620
And Agamemnon, the king,
says, I don't need you, man.

551
00:33:04,260 --> 00:33:06,320
So, Achilles refuses to fight, okay?

552
00:33:06,480 --> 00:33:09,220
The problem is, Achilles
is the greatest warrior

553
00:33:09,880 --> 00:33:11,960
of the Greeks. And the Trojans,

554
00:33:13,360 --> 00:33:17,480
led by Hector, who is a son of Priam,

555
00:33:18,020 --> 00:33:20,840
he sees an opportunity because
Achilles refuses to fight.

556
00:33:21,080 --> 00:33:24,220
And Hector leads the
Trojan army out of Troy.

557
00:33:24,460 --> 00:33:26,520
And they're destroying the Greeks.

558
00:33:27,520 --> 00:33:30,940
And the Trojans are about
to crush the Greek army.

559
00:33:31,260 --> 00:33:33,240
So, the Greek generals say to Agamemnon,

560
00:33:33,420 --> 00:33:39,100
Could you please beg Achilles
to return to the battlefield?

561
00:33:40,260 --> 00:33:42,600
And they go and they talk to Achilles.

562
00:33:42,920 --> 00:33:44,900
And Achilles basically says, Screw off.

563
00:33:45,020 --> 00:33:47,900
I'm not helping you
guys, okay? His friend,

564
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,000
Patroclus, okay?

565
00:33:50,440 --> 00:33:52,680
Patroclus is basically
like his younger brother.

566
00:33:53,300 --> 00:33:56,460
He feels sorry for the Greeks,
so he pretends to be Achilles

567
00:33:56,460 --> 00:33:59,180
and goes off to battle against Hector.

568
00:33:59,640 --> 00:34:03,940
Hector kills Patroclus and
this angers Achilles, okay?

569
00:34:04,100 --> 00:34:08,060
Achilles is so angry that he jumps
into the battle and he kills Hector.

570
00:34:08,540 --> 00:34:13,020
Once he kills Hector, he does
something very odd, okay?

571
00:34:13,480 --> 00:34:16,760
Usually, when you kill
someone's body, you return

572
00:34:16,760 --> 00:34:19,560
that body to your enemy for a ransom.

573
00:34:20,100 --> 00:34:22,180
Because the belief back then is,

574
00:34:22,180 --> 00:34:24,860
only if you bury your dead can

575
00:34:24,860 --> 00:34:28,800
the dead find peace in
the afterworld, okay?

576
00:34:30,500 --> 00:34:33,540
But Achilles is so angry at Hector that

577
00:34:33,540 --> 00:34:36,900
he's torturing Hector's body, which

578
00:34:36,900 --> 00:34:38,600
is torturing Priam.

579
00:34:39,680 --> 00:34:42,420
But even after Achilles does this,

580
00:34:43,680 --> 00:34:46,120
he can't sleep and

581
00:34:46,120 --> 00:34:50,760
he feels tremendous sadness, even though
he's avenged the death of Patroclus.

582
00:34:50,860 --> 00:34:54,680
And the reason why is, in
his heart, Achilles knows

583
00:34:55,600 --> 00:35:00,260
he was the one responsible
for killing Patroclus, right?

584
00:35:00,440 --> 00:35:03,800
Because if he didn't get into the
stupid fight with Agamemnon, and

585
00:35:03,800 --> 00:35:08,140
if he did not refuse the Greeks when they
requested help, then Patroclus wouldn't have died.

586
00:35:08,500 --> 00:35:11,480
So it's because Achilles
was so stubborn and so proud

587
00:35:12,140 --> 00:35:13,880
that his friend Patroclus died.

588
00:35:14,100 --> 00:35:15,400
So he feels tremendous guilt

589
00:35:16,180 --> 00:35:17,620
for what happened.

590
00:35:17,840 --> 00:35:22,140
And his guilt turns into an
intense hatred for Hector.

591
00:35:22,180 --> 00:35:24,400
That's why he's torturing Hector's body.

592
00:35:25,960 --> 00:35:29,100
Then what happens is Priam, King Priam,

593
00:35:29,140 --> 00:35:32,120
who can't sleep either because
his son is being tortured, okay?

594
00:35:32,220 --> 00:35:35,980
His son is dead, but his soul is
still being tortured by Achilles.

595
00:35:36,260 --> 00:35:40,160
He sneaks into Achilles' tent, okay?

596
00:35:40,600 --> 00:35:44,220
And he's right behind Achilles while
Achilles is talking to his generals.

597
00:35:44,560 --> 00:35:47,700
And at this point, remember,
Achilles doesn't see him.

598
00:35:47,800 --> 00:35:52,160
He's standing behind Achilles. He can
take his knife and stab Achilles' head.

599
00:35:52,180 --> 00:35:55,460
He can stab Achilles' neck, right?
And that's what most people would do.

600
00:35:55,760 --> 00:35:57,100
But Priam doesn't do that.

601
00:35:57,810 --> 00:36:00,640
Priam instead kneels down and

602
00:36:00,640 --> 00:36:03,420
kisses the hand of Achilles,

603
00:36:04,180 --> 00:36:06,000
which forces Achilles

604
00:36:07,320 --> 00:36:10,500
to be in awe of this king

605
00:36:11,010 --> 00:36:13,900
who has knelt down before him.

606
00:36:14,080 --> 00:36:16,800
And he admires Priam's courage

607
00:36:17,720 --> 00:36:20,260
and love for his son so much

608
00:36:20,260 --> 00:36:23,280
that he feels tremendous shame and

609
00:36:23,280 --> 00:36:25,140
remorse for what he's done to Hector.

610
00:36:25,260 --> 00:36:29,580
And he returns Hector's body
to Priam as compensation.

611
00:36:30,960 --> 00:36:33,880
And that's how the Iliad ends, okay?

612
00:36:34,140 --> 00:36:38,860
The main message of the Iliad is it's
not war that creates civilization.

613
00:36:39,260 --> 00:36:41,360
It is love that creates civilization.

614
00:36:42,280 --> 00:36:45,800
It is Priam's love for Hector

615
00:36:45,800 --> 00:36:49,980
that gives him the courage
to defeat Achilles,

616
00:36:50,260 --> 00:36:51,520
in battle.

617
00:36:51,760 --> 00:36:54,520
And in this defeat, Achilles
becomes a better person

618
00:36:54,900 --> 00:36:57,460
because he's able to forgive himself and

619
00:36:57,460 --> 00:37:00,420
he's able to do what is right and just

620
00:37:00,420 --> 00:37:04,900
and return Hector to his father, okay?

621
00:37:05,280 --> 00:37:08,220
That's the Iliad. As you can imagine,

622
00:37:08,500 --> 00:37:13,060
this is extremely complicated psychology.

623
00:37:14,560 --> 00:37:19,260
And it forces you to think deeply
about who we are as humans, okay?

624
00:37:19,260 --> 00:37:22,340
Okay? Okay?

625
00:37:24,900 --> 00:37:27,760
Does that make sense?
And the third thing that

626
00:37:27,760 --> 00:37:30,540
is shocking about the Iliad
is the use of metaphors.

627
00:37:33,240 --> 00:37:35,020
So what are metaphors?

628
00:37:35,660 --> 00:37:40,420
Metaphors are connections between
things that were unseen, okay?

629
00:37:40,580 --> 00:37:44,980
So for example, if I
say, the sky is a snail.

630
00:37:46,540 --> 00:37:48,940
You're like, oh, I didn't know that.

631
00:37:48,940 --> 00:37:51,420
I didn't know that. Okay? Do you
understand? That's what a metaphor is.

632
00:37:51,440 --> 00:37:55,440
A metaphor is connecting two things
that before were not connected.

633
00:37:55,640 --> 00:37:59,740
If you think about it, what
this is is a new thought.

634
00:38:01,640 --> 00:38:03,900
And there are lots of
metaphors in the Iliad, okay?

635
00:38:04,280 --> 00:38:05,780
So essentially,

636
00:38:07,060 --> 00:38:09,820
metaphors teach you how to think, okay?

637
00:38:09,960 --> 00:38:12,740
They are the tools for thought.

638
00:38:14,820 --> 00:38:18,220
So these are the three distinct
characteristics of the Iliad

639
00:38:18,220 --> 00:38:21,980
that make it unique in the world, okay?

640
00:38:22,180 --> 00:38:24,700
It's switching perspectives
all the time, which

641
00:38:24,700 --> 00:38:27,780
creates empathy, right?

642
00:38:28,020 --> 00:38:32,160
It talks about human psychology all
the time, which creates imagination.

643
00:38:33,200 --> 00:38:35,980
And it uses metaphors, which

644
00:38:35,980 --> 00:38:38,940
enables you to think much more
deeply about the world, okay?

645
00:38:39,720 --> 00:38:41,440
If you put these three things together,

646
00:38:42,060 --> 00:38:45,500
what this is, ultimately, is

647
00:38:48,220 --> 00:38:52,820
a theory of human, okay?

648
00:38:52,960 --> 00:38:56,160
It's a theory of what it
means to be a human being.

649
00:38:57,100 --> 00:39:00,920
Before, we thought human
beings fought over land.

650
00:39:01,160 --> 00:39:04,580
They fought over a
woman, like Helen, okay?

651
00:39:05,460 --> 00:39:06,820
They struggled for power.

652
00:39:07,500 --> 00:39:11,180
What Homer is saying is, what
it means to be human is someone

653
00:39:11,180 --> 00:39:13,080
who has empathy, imagination,

654
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:17,720
and the willingness to think.

655
00:39:18,220 --> 00:39:21,640
Okay? Only if you're willing to see,

656
00:39:21,760 --> 00:39:23,820
feel, and think, are you human?

657
00:39:25,820 --> 00:39:28,460
This is a new theory of human

658
00:39:29,580 --> 00:39:31,340
that becomes the basis

659
00:39:32,060 --> 00:39:36,640
for Greek civilization. And

660
00:39:36,640 --> 00:39:39,580
that's why the Greeks believed
the founder of the civilization

661
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:42,280
was not a general, he was not a king,

662
00:39:42,440 --> 00:39:45,280
it was a poet named Homer.

663
00:39:46,520 --> 00:39:50,120
Okay? And it's because of the Iliad

664
00:39:50,120 --> 00:39:52,180
that they all read and memorized

665
00:39:52,840 --> 00:39:55,480
and they could recite, okay?

666
00:39:55,520 --> 00:39:59,460
Because, again, this is an oral culture where
you're trained to have a very strong memory.

667
00:39:59,860 --> 00:40:01,980
And because they memorized the Iliad,

668
00:40:02,260 --> 00:40:07,040
it further transformed them as humans,

669
00:40:07,320 --> 00:40:10,220
okay? This is a new theory
of what it means to be human.

670
00:40:10,320 --> 00:40:13,020
And this becomes the basis
for Greek civilization,

671
00:40:13,400 --> 00:40:16,360
which then becomes the basis
for Western civilization.

672
00:40:18,120 --> 00:40:20,980
And it's because of these
three reasons, the polis,

673
00:40:23,220 --> 00:40:26,420
the alphabet, and Homer, that

674
00:40:26,420 --> 00:40:31,220
we have Western civilization
as we know it today.

675
00:40:32,100 --> 00:40:33,340
Okay? Any questions so far?

676
00:40:35,900 --> 00:40:37,220
Any questions so far, guys?

677
00:40:39,020 --> 00:40:44,800
All right. Now I'm going to spend
some time and discuss, okay,

678
00:40:44,900 --> 00:40:50,820
why is Greek civilization different
from Chinese civilization?

679
00:40:51,220 --> 00:40:53,240
Okay? And this will help
you better understand

680
00:40:53,900 --> 00:40:57,160
Western civilization. So
the first question is,

681
00:40:57,910 --> 00:41:00,960
why is it that Greeks developed alphabet,

682
00:41:01,360 --> 00:41:05,600
okay, the alphabet, and the Chinese
did not develop the alphabet?

683
00:41:06,620 --> 00:41:08,420
Okay? And the answer is this.

684
00:41:08,940 --> 00:41:10,380
The answer is,

685
00:41:13,660 --> 00:41:16,270
Greece was not an isolated culture.

686
00:41:16,270 --> 00:41:21,050
Okay? So the people who actually
developed the alphabet were the Egyptians.

687
00:41:22,110 --> 00:41:25,570
Okay? Egyptians. And the reason why is,

688
00:41:26,650 --> 00:41:29,310
Egypt was constantly in
contact and communication

689
00:41:29,970 --> 00:41:34,310
with many different societies and cultures,
including the Sumerians and the Greeks.

690
00:41:35,530 --> 00:41:40,250
And they could adopt new practices
to advance their language.

691
00:41:41,430 --> 00:41:44,010
Okay? So it was the Greeks, it
was the Egyptians who developed

692
00:41:45,390 --> 00:41:49,890
the alphabet. The
Phoenicians were traders.

693
00:41:50,250 --> 00:41:53,510
And the Phoenicians connected the
Egyptian culture to everyone else.

694
00:41:53,690 --> 00:41:55,670
Okay? So it was the
Phoenicians who brought

695
00:41:56,310 --> 00:41:58,870
the alphabet to the Greeks, who, because

696
00:41:58,870 --> 00:42:01,730
they became illiterate, were
looking for a new language system.

697
00:42:02,510 --> 00:42:05,210
Okay? Does that make sense? That's why,

698
00:42:05,550 --> 00:42:07,350
that's how the Greeks got the alphabet.

699
00:42:08,090 --> 00:42:11,610
Again, the question is, why
didn't China develop the alphabet?

700
00:42:12,290 --> 00:42:14,850
And the answer is this. China,

701
00:42:14,850 --> 00:42:18,070
for most of its history, was
isolated from the rest of the world.

702
00:42:19,070 --> 00:42:21,130
But not only was China isolated, but

703
00:42:21,130 --> 00:42:24,010
it was stable for most of its history,

704
00:42:24,170 --> 00:42:25,850
because for most of Chinese history,

705
00:42:26,050 --> 00:42:29,790
China was run by a class of
people called scholar officials.

706
00:42:30,230 --> 00:42:33,450
Right? Confucian scholars.
What was their power?

707
00:42:33,670 --> 00:42:36,810
What was their secret power? It
was the ability to read and write.

708
00:42:37,370 --> 00:42:39,630
That's what differentiated
them from everyone else, right?

709
00:42:39,810 --> 00:42:42,990
That's what made them
indispensable to the emperor.

710
00:42:43,750 --> 00:42:46,190
That's why they were so powerful.

711
00:42:46,790 --> 00:42:49,250
And so when you have a
monopoly over literacy,

712
00:42:49,990 --> 00:42:51,350
you don't want to give it up.

713
00:42:51,490 --> 00:42:52,930
You want to increase it.

714
00:42:53,390 --> 00:42:54,790
And the way they did so

715
00:42:54,790 --> 00:42:58,550
is by creating a new language
called classical Chinese.

716
00:42:59,290 --> 00:43:01,010
Literally Chinese. Okay?
Does that make sense?

717
00:43:01,910 --> 00:43:05,510
That's why there was this
divergence between Greece

718
00:43:05,510 --> 00:43:06,950
and China at this time.

719
00:43:08,650 --> 00:43:12,330
Because China, literacy
was monopolized by an elite

720
00:43:12,330 --> 00:43:15,050
who benefited from this
monopoly. And therefore,

721
00:43:15,130 --> 00:43:18,290
they made this monopoly
much more effective

722
00:43:18,290 --> 00:43:21,550
by introducing a new language
called classical Chinese.

723
00:43:22,030 --> 00:43:24,110
That only they could master.

724
00:43:25,630 --> 00:43:26,830
Okay? Does that make sense, guys?

725
00:43:32,130 --> 00:43:33,290
Excuse me?

726
00:43:38,220 --> 00:43:42,290
Because the scholar officials,

727
00:43:42,490 --> 00:43:43,750
they were in charge of bureaucracy, right?

728
00:43:44,450 --> 00:43:47,470
If you're running a bureaucracy, you
need the ability to read and write.

729
00:43:47,870 --> 00:43:50,090
You need the ability to basically

730
00:43:52,330 --> 00:43:54,610
transport information from
one place to the next, right?

731
00:43:54,710 --> 00:43:56,310
That's through reading and
writing, through literacy.

732
00:43:57,630 --> 00:44:00,870
Does that make sense? So only
they could become bureaucrats.

733
00:44:02,930 --> 00:44:07,570
Okay? So, does that make sense?

734
00:44:08,210 --> 00:44:09,530
Okay. Any more questions?

735
00:44:10,710 --> 00:44:13,110
Okay. Second question is,

736
00:44:14,290 --> 00:44:17,070
why is it that Greeks had Homer

737
00:44:17,070 --> 00:44:20,370
and the Chinese, we Chinese,
we never had Homer?

738
00:44:20,610 --> 00:44:23,050
Okay? And again, the problem
are the scholar officials.

739
00:44:23,970 --> 00:44:25,390
If you look at Confucian thought,

740
00:44:27,890 --> 00:44:30,310
there's a hierarchy in
Confucian thought, right?

741
00:44:31,210 --> 00:44:32,750
At the very top are scholar officials.

742
00:44:33,090 --> 00:44:36,910
They're the most virtuous, they're the most well
-educated, they're the most cultivated, okay?

743
00:44:37,130 --> 00:44:38,390
They're the best people.

744
00:44:39,050 --> 00:44:44,910
Next to the, below the scholar
officials are the farmers

745
00:44:44,910 --> 00:44:46,830
and the artisans, right?

746
00:44:46,990 --> 00:44:49,210
Because they produce wealth for society.

747
00:44:49,570 --> 00:44:52,930
Below them are the merchants, right?

748
00:44:53,430 --> 00:44:55,450
And then at the very bottom are who?

749
00:44:56,470 --> 00:44:58,890
The artists, right?

